What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int x = 10;
    int y = 20;
    std::cout << (x > y ? x : y) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 5;
    int b = 5;
    std::cout << (a != b ? a - b : a + b) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Which of the following is the correct way to embed a conditional expression inside a `std::cout` statement without parentheses causing a compile error or wrong result?

```cpp
int n = 3;
// Attempt to print "odd" or "even"
```

The programmer wants this function to return the absolute value of `n`. What is wrong?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int absVal(int n) {
    return n >= 0 ? n : n * -1;
}
int main() {
    std::cout << absVal(-7) << "\n";  // expected: 7
    std::cout << absVal(3)  << "\n";  // expected: 3
    return 0;
}
```
